Methodology

Overview

This document describes the methodology used to develop and evaluate the Intent Preservation Benchmark v0.1.

The benchmark was designed to explore whether large language models faithfully preserve human intent when transforming complex clinical discharge documentation into patient-facing instructions. The methodology emphasizes reproducibility by documenting how benchmark cases were created, evaluated, and analyzed.



Research Question

The primary research question guiding this benchmark is:

Can large language models preserve human intent when transforming complex clinical information into patient-facing communication?

Rather than evaluating factual correctness alone, this benchmark investigates whether the meaning originally intended by a human expert remains intact after AI-assisted transformation.



Why Healthcare?

Healthcare was selected as the initial validation domain because it provides high-stakes communication scenarios where preserving human intent is essential.

Clinical discharge planning requires accurate transfer of medications, follow-up instructions, treatment plans, warning signs, and patient education. Even subtle changes in meaning can affect downstream communication between clinicians, patients, caregivers, and other healthcare professionals.

Although the benchmark begins in healthcare, the underlying evaluation framework is intended to be applicable to other safety-critical domains.



Benchmark Development

The initial benchmark consists of twenty synthetic clinical discharge planning scenarios representing medically complex patient cases.

Synthetic cases were used to:

Protect patient privacy.
Standardize benchmark construction.
Control case complexity.
Ensure reproducibility for future evaluations.

Each benchmark case was independently evaluated using the same methodology.



Model Evaluation

The initial benchmark evaluated Gemini 1.5 Flash.

For each benchmark case:

1. Original discharge documentation was prepared.
2. The language model generated patient-facing discharge instructions.
3. The generated output was manually compared with the original documentation.
4. Reviewer observations were documented.
5. Failures were categorized using standardized criteria.
6. Overall reliability was assessed.



Evaluation Process

Each benchmark case was reviewed across multiple evaluation dimensions, including:

Information Fidelity
Intent Preservation
Information Omission
Unsupported Assumptions
Hallucinated Clinical Information
Clinical Meaning Drift
Logical Consistency
Overall Reliability

A standardized evaluation rubric was used to improve consistency across benchmark cases.



Failure Analysis

Rather than recording isolated mistakes, recurring patterns observed during manual review were organized into standardized failure categories.

This process resulted in the initial Intent Preservation Failure Taxonomy, which classifies common ways language models fail to preserve human intent during complex information transformation.



Limitations

The current methodology has several limitations:

Twenty benchmark cases.
Evaluation of a single language model.
Manual scoring process.
No inter-rater reliability assessment.
Synthetic clinical scenarios.

These limitations are appropriate for an initial benchmark release and will inform future methodological improvements.



Future Methodology

Future versions of the benchmark will include:

Larger benchmark datasets.
Multiple language model comparisons.
Automated evaluation pipeline.
Clinical reviewer validation.
Inter-rater reliability analysis.
Expanded failure taxonomy.
Quantitative reliability metrics.

The long-term objective is to develop a reproducible evaluation methodology that can be applied across multiple high-stakes domains where preserving human intent is critical.
